\n  mutate(segment = row_number()) |>         # identify each separate activity interval\n  reframe(\n    sampleid = seq.int(start, end),          # expand start:end into all sample IDs\n    .by = c(trial, userid, act_code, activity, segment)\n  )\n\nuser_df = \n  tibble(userid = username, trial = expname, sampleid = seq.int(0, nrow(user01) - 1)) |>\n  bind_cols(user01) |>\n  left_join(sample_labels, by = c(\"userid\", \"trial\", \"sampleid\"))\n","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2025-09-19T18:18:30.754477Z","iopub.execute_input":"2025-09-19T18:18:30.755943Z","iopub.status.idle":"2025-09-19T18:18:31.008437Z","shell.execute_reply":"2025-09-19T18:18:31.006638Z"}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":3},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"As computers can only reflect signals in discrete samples, we have split the continuous timeframe data into epochs. We have chosen epochs as our units of measurement in order to delimitate the beginning and the end of an activity. Epochs reflect consecutive time windows and thus are suitable for this purpose. \n\nWe first split our data into epochs of 128 samples. \nEach epoch spans 2.56 seconds of signal.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"\n\nuser_df |>\n  mutate(epoch = sampleid %/% 128) |>     # add epoch ID (each epoch spans 2.56 sec of signal)\n  group_by(epoch) |>\n  summarise(mean_X1 = mean(X1), \n            mean_X2 = mean(X2), \n            mean_X3 = mean(X3)) |>\n  head()","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2025-09-19T18:18:31.012381Z","iopub.execute_input":"2025-09-19T18:18:31.013962Z","iopub.status.idle":"2025-09-19T18:18:31.060374Z","shell.execute_reply":"2025-09-19T18:18:31.057989Z"}},"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/html":"<table class=\"dataframe\">\n<caption>A tibble: 6 × 4</caption>\n<thead>\n\t<tr><th scope=col>epoch</th><th scope=col>mean_X1</th><th scope=col>mean_X2</th><th scope=col>mean_X3</th></tr>\n\t<tr><th scope=col>&lt;dbl&gt;</th><th scope=col>&lt;dbl&gt;</th><th scope=col>&lt;dbl&gt;</th><th scope=col>&lt;dbl&gt;</th></tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n\t<tr><td>0</td><td>0.908941</td><td>-0.1649089</td><td>0.25218100</td></tr>\n\t<tr><td>1</td><td>1.015723</td><td>-0.1324110</td><td>0.05088976</td></tr>\n\t<tr><td>2</td><td>1.019217</td><td>-0.1241102</td><td>0.09873047</td></tr>\n\t<tr><td>3</td><td>1.020074</td><td>-0.1254232</td><td>0.09264323</td></tr>\n\t<tr><td>4</td><td>1.020172</td><td>-0.1297960</td><td>0.08509115</td></tr>\n\t<tr><td>5</td><td>1.020757</td><td>-0.1285590</td><td>0.08496094</td></tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n","text/markdown":"\nA tibble: 6 × 4\n\n| epoch &lt;dbl&gt; | mean_X1 &lt;dbl&gt; | mean_X2 &lt;dbl&gt; | mean_X3 &lt;dbl&gt; |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| 0 | 0.908941 | -0.1649089 | 0.25218100 |\n| 1 | 1.015723 | -0.1324110 | 0.05088976 |\n| 2 | 1.019217 | -0.1241102 | 0.09873047 |\n| 3 | 1.020074 | -0.1254232 | 0.09264323 |\n| 4 | 1.020172 | -0.1297960 | 0.08509115 |\n| 5 | 1.020757 | -0.1285590 | 0.08496094 |\n\n","text/latex":"A tibble: 6 × 4\n\\begin{tabular}{llll}\n epoch & mean\\_X1 & mean\\_X2 & mean\\_X3\\\\\n <dbl> & <dbl> & <dbl> & <dbl>\\\\\n\\hline\n\t 0 & 0.908941 & -0.1649089 & 0.25218100\\\\\n\t 1 & 1.015723 & -0.1324110 & 0.05088976\\\\\n\t 2 & 1.019217 & -0.1241102 & 0.09873047\\\\\n\t 3 & 1.020074 & -0.1254232 & 0.09264323\\\\\n\t 4 & 1.020172 & -0.1297960 & 0.08509115\\\\\n\t 5 & 1.020757 & -0.1285590 & 0.08496094\\\\\n\\end{tabular}\n","text/plain":"  epoch mean_X1  mean_X2    mean_X3   \n1 0     0.908941 -0.1649089 0.25218100\n2 1     1.015723 -0.1324110 0.05088976\n3 2     1.019217 -0.1241102 0.09873047\n4 3     1.020074 -0.1254232 0.09264323\n5 4     1.020172 -0.1297960 0.08509115\n6 5     1.020757 -0.1285590 0.08496094"},"metadata":{}}],"execution_count":4},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"**Time domain features**\n\nWe obtained statistics from signals.\n\nOur time domain features include location measures, spread measures, and histogram shape descriptors.\n\n**Common statistics:**\n* Mean - investigating the signal amplitude\n* SD - spread around the mean\n* Median - adds robustness to outliers\n* Min & Max - can help investigate spikes in the signal\n* Range - amplitude spread measure\n* Covariance - investigates how signals in different directions varied together in the 3D-space. helps distinguish movement across space.\n* IQR - adds robustness to outliers\n* Quantiles - another shape feature\n* Skew - asymmetry in the shape\n* Kurtosis - severity of the tailedness of the signal\n\n**Other statistics:**\n* Lagged correlation - computes the correlation between x and a time shifted y. Helps investigate temporal dependencies in the signal.\n* Power - average squared amplitude of the signal, indicating how much it deviates from 0. Can help distinguish the intensity of signals. \n* Entropy - measure of average uncertainty regarding the potential states of a signal, higher entropy indicating more unpredictability in the signal's patterns. \n* Signal energy - total power of the samples. Sum of squares formula used to estimate \"intensity\" of the activity, which can be used for distinguishing walking from\n* Sign changes - counts how many times a signal changes its sign (from + to -),and can help distinguish lying down from standing.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Helper functions\nmost_common_value = function(x) {\n    counts = table(x, useNA='no')\n    most_frequent = which.max(counts)\n    return(names(most_frequent))\n}\n\n## Feature functions (time domain)\n\n# Lagged correlation\nlagged_cor = function(x, y=x, lag=0) {\n    r_lagged = cor(x, dplyr::lag(y, lag), use='pairwise')\n    return(r_lagged)\n}\n\n# Entropy\nentropy = function(x, nbreaks = nclass.Sturges(x)) {\n    r = range(x)\n    x_binned = findInterval(x, seq(r[1], r[2], len = nbreaks))\n    h = tabulate(x_binned, nbins = nbreaks)\n    p = h/sum(h)\n    -sum(p[p>0] * log(p[p>0]))\n}\n\n# Power \npower = function(x) {\n    power = mean(x^2)\n    return(power)\n}\n\n#IQR \ninterquartile_range = function(x) {\n    return(IQR(x, na.rm=T))\n}\n\n# Signal energy\nsignal_energy = function(x) {\n    return(sum(x^2)/length(x)) \n}\n\n# Sign changes\nsign_changes = function(x) {\n    sum(diff(sign(x)) != 0, na.rm = TRUE) \n}\n","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2025-09-19T18:18:31.064145Z","iopub.execute_input":"2025-09-19T18:18:31.065567Z","iopub.status.idle":"2025-09-19T18:18:31.091447Z","shell.execute_reply":"2025-09-19T18:18:31.089738Z"}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":5},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"We added a variable to distinguish epochs from signal samples. For each epoch, we extracted all statistical features and stored them in a new file.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Compute features per epoch:\n\nusertimedom = user_df |>\n\n  # add an epoch ID variable (one epoch = 2.56 sec)\n  mutate(epoch = sampleid %/% 128) |>\n\n  # extract statistical features from each epoch\n  group_by(epoch) |>\n  summarise(\n  # Activity label for the epoch = most common value (mode)\n      activity = most_common_value(c(\"-\", activity)),\n\n      # Keep starting sample ID of the epoch\n      sampleid = sampleid[1],\n\n      # Signal featuresa\n      mean_X1 = mean(X1), \n      mean_X2 = mean(X2), \n      mean_X3 = mean(X3),\n      sd_X1   = sd(X1), \n      sd_X2 = sd(X2),\n      sd_X3 = sd(X3),\n      median_X1 = median(X1),\n      median_X2 = median(X2),\n      median_X3 = median(X3),\n      min_X1 = min(X1),\n      min_X2 = min(X2),\n      min_X3 = min(X3),\n      max_X1 = max(X1),\n      max_X2 = max(X2),\n      max_X3 = max(X3),\n      range_X1 = range(X1)[2] - range(X1)[1],\n      range_X2 = range(X2)[2] - range(X2)[1],\n      rangeX3 = range(X3)[2] - range(X3)[1],\n      cov_X1X2 = cov(X1, X2),\n      cov_X1X3 = cov(X1, X3),\n      cov_X2X3 = cov(X2, X3),\n      q25_X1  = quantile(X1, .25),\n      q75_X1 = quantile(X1, .75),\n      q25_X2 = quantile(X2, .25)